{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496933"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:59:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:59:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1440"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1440"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.08,0.64,0.11,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53959"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1440"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39430"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3994"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16251"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53959"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless swelling over the back of his head. This has been present for about ten years and has been getting slowly larger. It has not bothered him much previously, but now his friends keep asking him what it is. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He practices sun safety, regularly applies sunscreen and limits outdoor time. There is no personal history of cancer or family history of similar lesions or cancer. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The swelling is firm, non-tender, and rubbery in consistency. The overlying skin is mobile, and the mass can be moved beneath the skin. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epidermoid cyst","Sebaceous cyst","Lipoma","Dermoid cyst","Pilomatrixoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this patient is a \u003Cstrong\u003Elipoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Lipomas are common benign tumours composed of mature fat cells. They typically present as slow-growing, painless, soft to rubbery masses in the subcutaneous tissue. The key features in this case supporting a lipoma diagnosis are the long-standing nature (10 years), gradual growth, and the ability to move the mass beneath the skin (positive slippage sign).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are common benign cysts lined with stratified squamous epithelium. While they can occur on the scalp, they typically present as smaller nodules and often have a visible central punctum, which is not mentioned in this case. They also tend to be more fixed to the skin rather than freely mobile beneath it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESebaceous cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are actually a misnomer and are typically epidermoid cysts. True sebaceous cysts are rare. They present similarly to epidermoid cysts and would be unlikely to grow to the size described in this case over such a long period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are congenital lesions containing elements from multiple germ layers. While they can occur on the scalp, they are typically diagnosed in childhood, with 70% of cases found in children under five years old. The patient\u0027s age and the recent onset of growth make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPilomatrixoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign tumour originating from hair follicle cells. While it can occur on the scalp, it is relatively rare and typically presents as a small, firm, sometimes bluish nodule. It is more common in children and young adults and would be an unusual diagnosis for a long-standing, large scalp mass in a middle-aged adult.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile imaging or biopsy could provide definitive diagnosis, the clinical presentation strongly suggests a lipoma. Management options for lipomas include observation or surgical excision if the lesion is bothersome or for cosmetic reasons. In this case, given the size and location, the patient might consider removal for cosmetic reasons.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lipomas are typically slow-growing soft, painless, mobile subcutaneous nodules with a positive slippage sign, favouring fatty areas of the trunk, neck and forearms.","Lipomas can occur on the scalp and may grow to a significant size over many years."],"references":["Leung LK. Differential diagnosis of soft scalp lumps. BMJ Case Rep. 2011 Nov 15;2011:bcr0720114492. Available at: https://casereports.bmj.com/content/2011/bcr.07.2011.4492# \\","Kolb L, Yarrarapu SNS, Ameer MA, et al. Lipoma. In: StatPearls [Online].  Updated 2022 Sep 26. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507906/","Shareef S, Ettefagh L. Dermoid Cyst. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 Aug 29. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560573/","Raposo AC, Correia A, Vaz J, Alves L, Morais P. Firm nodule in the scalp. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019 May;48(5):294-297. Available at: https://doi.org/10.31128/AJGP-10-18-4721"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39430"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1440"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18630"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18630"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8fb257a0-e786-4928-b1d5-d3af92f1c262.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8fb257a0-e786-4928-b1d5-d3af92f1c262.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39430"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T12:01:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-28T12:02:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1440"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53959"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","